<br>
I have on a number of occasions stolen agro (like most skills, evade has a success ratio of around 2/3).  At these times I can usually turn off attack, take a couple of steps back and the mob turns back to the tank.  Wait a second and step back in, and the mob turns and smacks me - despite me not having hit it since.<br>
<br>
Obviously, the optimal use of taunt (ie in order to produce the most hate generated by the skill without having the mob actually turn) is when somebody is just about to generate enough agro to turn the mob.  Seeing as nobody really <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>knows</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> when that's going to be, the two basic strategies (mashing and finessing) have developed.<br>
<br>
If you're in a situation where everybody else is generating vast amounts of agro over you (ie when it's likely that somebody is nearing that turning point every time Taunt refreshes), mashing would appear to be the optimal strategy.  The downside is that should the mob get away from you, it's going to have plenty of time to beat on the poor victim while you wait for refresh.<br>
<br>
If you can stay at or near the top of the list however (because everybody is keeping their own hate down through evade, jolt, archery, concussion, natural agro decay etc), then situational use is clearly superior, as it minimizes the time that the mob gets to beat on anybody.  The disadvantage is that you might fail Taunt, giving it a full refresh cycle to beat on its victim. <p><center> <table border="0" cellspacing="0" style="background-color: black;"> <tr><td colspan="3"><img src="http://ojaste.dhs.org/~shariin/Shariin.gif" alt="Shariin"></td></tr> <tr style="color: white; background: rgb(40,35,40); text-align: left; font: italic bold 10pt sans-serif;"> <td>Shariin Shadowblade</td> <td style="text-align: center; color: rgb(128,128,128);">Soldiers of Light</td> <td style="text-align: right;">Assassin</td> </tr> </table> </center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=viken>Viken</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/20/03 5:13:50 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Show me the money</span><hr size=1> I would agree with the hypothesis that there is a modified (based on range, sit/stand, low hp) hate list. IF this is the case, then I think the best way to use taunt button is to place your taunts immediately after your group members land spells (debuffs, nukes, etc...). You need to keep spell emotes on for group members and start learning the key spell emotes for each class. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ragnok>Ragnok</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 12<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/21/03 1:02:10 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Show me the money</span><hr size=1> As an addition I want to clarify that my posts were regarding non-raid situations only. When you are in a raid situation, the amount of variables involved becomes impossible to guestimate, unless you have verants actual agro algorythm sitting infront of you. Unless your raid force is disciplined, the warrior has to mash taunt simply because he can lose agro faster than taunt refreshes. So in that sense, sometimes we will have to mash without question at times.<br>
<br>
Most of us have posted our thoughts on what method is used to calculate agro, a tangent on the purpose of this thread, but while we are taking stabs in the dark I will as well. Being a programmer myself, I believe the most efficient and easy way to calculate agro is to only maintain one list. Creating and modifying multiple lists is not only calculation intensive, but also requires multiple redundant algorythm's just to match the lists. Here is how i see it:<br>
<br>
a.)I see one 'list' per mob<br>
<br>
b.)I see the agro engine updating that list in very fast increments. Much smaller than a tick, lets call it a tock. Every tock, the list runs another cycle and recalculates agro. Since some damage will happen at any given time (AoE,Dot), a tock really needs to be the smallest amount of time measurement that eq uses.<br>
<br>
c.)I see every spell and skill tagged in the database with the amount of agro 'points' that it adds to the list. Resists could even have a different amount, but i don't see that as the case. damage points could translate directly into agro points for arguments sake.<br>
<br>
d.)Player actions trigger 'events' that add agro to the list as soon as they fire off: <br>
1.) For example, when a player sits down, an event fires off that adds x amount of agro to the list. The amount it adds could even be multiplied based on how much damage they have done, or maybe based on where they are currently on the agro list. Either way, when a player sits, if they have done enough damage, they move to the top of the list, and the mob rushes/casts on/summons them.<br>
<br>
I think the above approach works for all situations, and is very, very simple to maintain and explain. Lets try to:<br>
<br>
Taunting: Assuming taunt works, you move to the top of the list by 1 point. You get agro as soon as it hits, but you dont keep agro. why did you lose agro right away?<br>
<br>
1.) cause a few tocks later, the ranger/rogue/monk was still out-damaging you, and was therefore back on top of the list.<br>
<br>
2.) The wizard that just manaburned at 80% life just sat down. When he sat down the event fires and adds a ton of agro points to his profile on the list, moving him to the top of the list. The moster summons him. If summon hasnt refreshed, the un-rooted mob rushes him. The wizard sees the charging mob and stands up. The mob turns back to you. Why? Because the next tock after the wizard stands the agro list once again goes through an algorythm and puts the wizard back to where he was in the list before he sat down (approx.).<br>
<br>
<br>
A caster gets slammed and is now at 1 bubble of health. What happens here?<br>
<br>
1.) Every tock, all agro lists in the game are updated. we've established that. Lets say the caster is on 3 agro lists (3 mobs). The next tock after the caster has only one bubble of health, the caster is kept at the top of the agro list every tock until hes dead or healed. Since hes now at the top of all agro lists, all 3 mobs summon/cast/rush him. No amount of taunting or damage will help, because the system keeps him at the top of each mobs agro list because of his health. When he dies, the next person on the list becomes #1 and gets agro.<br>
<br>
The mob is rooted. Lets try to explain this situation:<br>
<br>
1.) All agro rules apply except that it cant move. If he can summon, he summons the top person on his agro list every time it refreshes. If he can't summon, he hits the highest person on his list that he can reach. If the closest thing he can reach is the gimp ranger that hit him for 10 points, hes going to hit him. If the closest toon to him is somebody that hasnt hit/casted on him, but is kos to him, hes gonna hit that toon.<br>
<br>
I could go on and on with examples, but since half of you have probably given up and continued on to the next post before getting this far, ill end it here. I think this is pretty straightforward, and can account for all aspects of agro.<br>
<br>
