<br>
On most single target raids, it's probably best to use the &quot;mash&quot; method.<br>
<br>
On most experience groups, the &quot;when you lose, or pedict that you will lose aggro&quot; method is probably best.<br>
<br>
I'd support that summation. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=thorbadintriton>Thorbadin Triton</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 21<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/21/03 4:49:12 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   hey</span><hr size=1> You guys make it feel as if taunt was on a 30 sec refresh time.  It's like 5 sec.  So if you mash all the time taunt will be unavailable for half of the time assuming you lose aggro, which is about 2.5 sec.  In reality you won't mash perfectly and the average time you wait will be lower then 2.5 sec.  Let's say 2 sec.   That's not a big deal whoever you put it imo.<br>
<br>
Another thing about the existence of 2 lists for aggro.  I did not bring that up but someone did I think at the start of that thread somewhere and said it like it was a fact or something. What we know for sure is that some action simple adds more aggro to the list and some others modify the already existing aggro.  Many mobs and some players spell like voice of terris simply affect your aggro by adding a % like +20% to your actual aggro.  Basically these effects work as a &quot;mask&quot; over your actual total.  When you lose these effects, you lose the benefice/penality but your actual aggro  do not change.  Range would fall in that category, creating some kind of mask over your actual hate by how close/far you are from the mob.  Certains mob behavior are of course gonna be different but that's in general.<br>
<br>
The idea of having 2 lists from a programming standpoint is not that bad for some reasons.  It's also supported by additionnal evidence I'll cover in a sec.<br>
<br>
So you have the first list.  Everyone that aggroed a mob is on that list with their actual hate.  If we assume we have 2 lists that first list does not need to be sorted since aggro is determine in the second one.  Gratz on finding the list used for rampage.  Each time you do something your number is taken from the first list then modified by whatever aggro spell you have, by your range and other conditions like sitting, etc then it goes in the other list and calculate your new number.  Swapping you with another if totals change.  Then when it's time to determine mob behavior, that mob go into that sorted list and see who it should be attacking.<br>
<br>
The 2nd list can be much smaller then the first one and it would be very simple to simply not do any sorting/update if you know that the person on that list is not gonna be in the top 10 or something.  Remember that your modified hate total is calculated each time you do something worthwhile.<br>
<br>
Now, again from a programming standpoint, this look like a lot of manipulation to do in real time to make certain that everything work right.  This could also explain why out of all the mmorpg I know EQ is really the only game with a hate list worth @#%$. You also have to add to that that the AI can cheat on things that will be transparent to us anyway or use randoms numbers on stuff to simplify things and cut on calculations.   This would also explain why sometime the AI do things differently then we thought it would (wtf, I just nuked for 200 dmg when the mob was at 200 feet, I got summoned and killed).<br>
<br>
Anyway, it's rambling, but just saying it's possible.<br>
<br>
Thorbadin<br>
Triton<br>
